docs.abstract: The Awl’s publisher said “a steady decline in direct sales” was to blame. For years, the websites featured intelligent writing on eclectic subjects.
docs.snippet: The Awl’s publisher said “a steady decline in direct sales” was to blame. For years, the websites featured intelligent writing on eclectic subjects.
docs.lead_paragraph: For almost a decade, The Awl implored the world to “Be Less Stupid.” There was a “great big internet” out there, the editors cautioned. And by writing intelligently about offbeat topics — from a locket meant to hold “mad money” to a deeply unsatisfying West Elm couch called “the Peggy” — The Awl and its sister sites did their best to live up to the motto.

headline.main: The Awl and The Hairpin, Eccentric Showcases for Writers, Are Shutting Down

docs.abstract: The technology inside Amazon’s new convenience store, opening Monday in downtown Seattle, enables a shopping experience like no other — including no checkout lines.
docs.snippet: The technology inside Amazon’s new convenience store, opening Monday in downtown Seattle, enables a shopping experience like no other — including no checkout lines.
docs.lead_paragraph: SEATTLE — The first clue that there’s something unusual about Amazon’s store of the future hits you right at the front door. It feels as if you are entering a subway station. A row of gates guard the entrance to the store, known as Amazon Go, allowing in only people with the store’s smartphone app.

headline.main: Inside Amazon Go, a Store of the Future
headline.print_headline: Inside Amazon’s Store of the Future

docs.abstract: More than two dozen civil rights organizations asked the tech giant to stop selling its image recognition system to law enforcement agencies.
docs.snippet: More than two dozen civil rights organizations asked the tech giant to stop selling its image recognition system to law enforcement agencies.
docs.lead_paragraph: SEATTLE — In late 2016, Amazon introduced a new online service that could help identify faces and other objects in images, offering it to anyone at a low cost through its giant cloud computing division, Amazon Web Services.

headline.main: Amazon Pushes Facial Recognition to Police. Critics See Surveillance Risk.
headline.print_headline: A.C.L.U. Sees ‘a Grave Threat’ In Amazon’s Facial Recognition
